linux, bsd: compare boot times with fuzz when eliminating duplicates

On Linux and Darwin the reported boot time can vary on a single boot,
likely caused by things like NTP adjustments and system clock getting
resynchronized with RTC after a resume from suspend (RTCs have mostly only
1-second resolution, so this operation can cause rounding errors).

This variation causes duplicate uptime entries to appear, which is,
naturally, a rather bad thing.

To work it around let's compare the boot time with some fuzz when
eliminating duplicate entries.

A 30-second window should be a good compromise between what was reported as
the maximum boot time dispersion and a realistic minimum inter-boot
interval.

commit.message:
Fix non-POSIX use of echo -n

Use printf instead of echo -n because echo -n is not portable and
doesn't have the desired effect of suppressing the trailing newline
(printing instead a literal "-n") on some systems such as macOS.
